\rmk{
\p{If I had to teach abstract algebra to undergraduates, I am torn between the traditional approaches (starting from van der Waerden's \textit{Moderne Algebra} onwards) which I just outlined, and more modern adaptations which wrap everything in the framework of category theory. Aluffi's \textit{Algebra: Chapter Zero} seemingly attempts a happy medium, and I am unhappy with it.}
\p{One fortunate aspect to Forester is that I'm not forced to choose one or the other. I can outline the "traditional" presentation of topics, and the "modern" presentation of topics, and allow the reader to pick which manner of presentation they wish to peruse.}}